{"title_page": "2002 Hong Kong Sevens", "text_new": "{{Infobox Rugby Sevens\n| series = <small>'''[[2001\u201302 World Sevens Series|IRB Sevens III]]'''</small>\n| countries = {{flag|Hong Kong}}\n| date = 22\u201324 March 2002\n| champions1 = {{ru7|ENG}}\n| runnersup1 = {{ru7|FIJ}}\n| champions2 = {{ru7|RSA}}\n| runnersup2 = {{ru7|SCO}}\n| champions3 = {{ru7|MAR}}\n| runnersup3 = {{ru7|TPE}}\n| matches = 45\n| tries = \n| top point scorer = \n| top try scorer = \n| prevseason = [[2001 Hong Kong Sevens|2001]]\n| nextseason = [[2003 Hong Kong Sevens|2003]]\n}}\nThe '''2002 Hong Kong Sevens''' was an international [[rugby sevens]] tournament that took place at the [[Hong Kong Stadium]] between 22\u201324 March 2002. It was the 27th edition of the [[Hong Kong Sevens]] and was the seventh tournament of the [[2001\u201302 World Sevens Series]]. Twenty-four teams competed in the tournament and were separated into six groups of four with the top eight teams qualifying through to the cup tournament.\n\nAfter winning their three group matches, [[England national rugby sevens team|England]] went on to win their first Hong Kong title defeating [[Fiji national rugby sevens team|Fiji]] in the final by a score of 33\u201320. In the plate-final, [[South Africa national rugby sevens team|South Africa]] defeated [[Scotland national rugby sevens team|Scotland]] while [[Morocco national rugby sevens team|Morocco]] took home the bowl defeating [[Chinese Taipei national rugby sevens team|Chinese Taipei]].\n\n==Teams==\nCompared to other tournament of the series, the Hong Kong Sevens had 24 teams compete for the title instead of the regular sixteen teams that usually competed in a World Series event. The official announcement of teams was revealed on the 22 January 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hksevens.com.hk/news/2002Jan22.htm|title=Teams announced for the 2002 Credit Suisse First Boston Hong Kong Sevens|location=Hong Kong|date=22 January 2002|publisher=HK Sevens|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20020411153519/http://www.hksevens.com.hk/news/2002Jan22.htm|archive-date=11 April 2002}}</ref> Almost a month later, [[Italy national rugby sevens team|Italy]] withdrew from the Hong Kong Sevens and was replaced by [[Thailand national rugby sevens team|Thailand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hksevens.com.hk/news/2002feb22.htm|title=Thailand joins the 2002 Credit Suisse First Boston Hong Kong Sevens|location=Hong Kong|date=21 February 2002|publisher=HK Sevens|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20020622140948/http://www.hksevens.com.hk/news/2002feb22.htm|archive-date=22 June 2002}}</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* {{ru7|ARG}}\n* {{ru7|AUS}}\n* {{ru7|CAN}}\n* {{ru7|CHN}}\n* {{ru7|TPE}}\n* {{ru7|ENG}}\n* {{ru7|FIJ}}\n* {{ru7|FRA}}\n* {{ru7|HKG}}\n* {{ru7|JPN}}\n* {{ru7|MAR}}\n* {{ru7|NZL}}\n* {{ru7|PNG}}\n* {{ru7|POR}}\n* {{ru7|RUS}}\n* {{ru7|SAM}}\n* {{ru7|SCO}}\n* {{ru7|SIN}}\n* {{ru7|RSA}}\n* {{ru7|KOR}}\n* {{ru7|SRI}}\n* {{ru7|THA}}\n* {{ru7|USA}}\n* {{ru7|WAL}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Format==\nThe teams were drawn into six pools of four teams each. Each team played the other teams in their pool once, with three points awarded for a win, two points for a draw, and one point for a loss (no points awarded for a forfeit). The pool stage was played over the first two days of the tournament. The top team from each pool along with the two best runners-up advanced to the Cup quarter finals. The remaining four runners-up along with the four best third-placed teams advanced to the Plate quarter finals. The remaining eight teams went on to the Bowl quarter finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hksevens.com.hk/results_pool_format.htm|title=Format|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20020623180417/http://www.hksevens.com.hk/results_pool_format.htm|archive-date=23 June 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Pool stage==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|Key to colours in group tabl